          "body": "David's prayer is one of the finest doxological texts in the Old Testament and deserves to be read with the same attention given to Hannah's prayer (1 Samuel 2) or Mary's Magnificat (Luke 1:46-55). It opens with a blessing addressed to the covenant God of Israel 'forever and ever' (v. 10) — eternity as the frame before a word of praise is spoken. The fivefold doxology of verse 11 (greatness, power, glory, victory, majesty) exhausts human superlatives, then adds the ground beneath them: 'everything that is in the heavens and the earth' belongs to God, and the dominion is His. Verse 12 moves from God's universal sovereignty to His particular providence: riches and honor come from Him; He rules over all; strengthening and exalting anyone is His prerogative alone. The theological point accumulates pressure: by the time David reaches verse 14, the ground for human pride has been systematically demolished. 'But who am I and who are my people that we should be able to offer as generously as this?' The question expects no answer because the answer has already been given: nothing, without God. The climactic sentence — 'from Your hand we have given You' (v. 14) — is the chapter's theological center. Giving to God is a circle, not a transfer; all generosity is returned stewardship. Verse 15 deepens the humility with creation-language: we are sojourners, tenants, our days are like a shadow. The metaphor of shadow recalls Ecclesiastes and the Psalter (Psalm 102:11; 144:4); it positions the worshiper inside the framework of creaturely finitude. David then prays with transparency (v. 17): since God tests the heart and delights in uprightness, he offers his own integrity for inspection. He does not claim his gift was perfect; he claims it was willing and upright. The intercession of vv. 18-19 is the prayer's application: preserve this devotion in the people's hearts forever, direct their hearts to God, and give Solomon a whole heart to obey every commandment and complete the temple. The prayer thus moves from praise to humility to petition — and the petition is not for prosperity or victory but for the permanence of wholehearted devotion."
