          "title": "The coronation and its meaning — the throne of the LORD (29:20-25)",
          "body": "The corporate worship of verse 20 is the assembly's response to David's prayer: they bless the LORD, bow low, and do homage to both God and the king in a single act. The simultaneity is theologically significant — worship of God and honor to the king are not competing loyalties but integrated expressions of covenant order. The sacrificial celebration of verse 21 (one thousand bulls, one thousand rams, one thousand lambs, with drink offerings and sacrifices in abundance) is Israel's covenant meal before God, ratifying the great act of dedication that has just occurred. They ate and drank 'with great gladness' (v. 22) — the same *simchah* that marked the offering in v. 17. The coronation itself is spare in description but dense in theology (v. 23): Solomon 'sat on the throne of the LORD as king in place of David his father.' The phrase 'throne of the LORD' is unique to Chronicles (cf. 1 Chronicles 28:5) and the Chronicler's most explicit statement that the Davidic monarchy is a theocratic vice-regency. Solomon is not ascending his own throne but occupying God's. The LORD's exaltation of Solomon (v. 25) — bestowing 'royal majesty which had not been on any king before him in Israel' — confirms that the source of the new king's authority and splendor is divine, not dynastic. Human loyalty (v. 24) confirms what God has already ordained."
